  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2013099061" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2013099061" />
    <a title="Murtaza " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13716226-murtaza"><img alt="Murtaza " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531516448p2/13716226.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2013099061?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Murtaza " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Murtaza " href="/user/show/13716226-murtaza">Murtaza </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780892590575" href="/book/show/825445.Islam_Between_East_and_West">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13716226-murtaza?shelf=best-of-2017">best-of-2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13716226-murtaza?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2013099061" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer91345440429067139">In the Islamic conception of the world, mankind is unique among creation for serving as the vice-regent of the divine within the material world. While all created things are by nature obedient to the divine will and thus “Muslim,” only humans have the ability to choose whether to rebel or submit themselves to the natural order. Through their possession both an inner and outer life, humans potentially serve as the vehicle through which the divine attributes are projected into the material world, </span>
  <span id="freeText91345440429067139" style="display:none">In the Islamic conception of the world, mankind is unique among creation for serving as the vice-regent of the divine within the material world. While all created things are by nature obedient to the divine will and thus “Muslim,” only humans have the ability to choose whether to rebel or submit themselves to the natural order. Through their possession both an inner and outer life, humans potentially serve as the vehicle through which the divine attributes are projected into the material world, providing what we could describe as a moral influence upon a creation that would otherwise be deterministic and even mechanical.<br /><br />This book by Alija Ali Izetbegovic, former President of Bosnia, is a reflection on Islam as the “middle path” between living purely for the corporeal or metaphysical worlds. Whereas Christianity tries to counsel an unworldly “pure religion” and materialist ideologies like Marxism try to counsel an equally impractical “pure materialism,” Islam is unique for charting a course that melds both exterior and interior realities – both of which humans need to feel fulfilled and at peace with existence. In Islam, humans are encouraged to engage with both the material and divine worlds in equal measure. This philosophy of the religion is embodied in the very act of Islamic prayer, which combines physical activity with meditative reflection. Izetbegovic’s conception of Islam is a consistent echo of Muhammad Asad, Ibn Arabi and a long line of Islamic philosophers reaching back into early antiquity who explained the attraction and practicality of Islam. Properly conceived, Islamic practices offer simultaneously spiritual salvation and a means for ordering the world for mankind’s wellbeing, merging both spheres of existence into a healthy balance.<br /><br />Over the course of the book, Izetbegovic conducts a comparative analysis of modern materialist ideologies with religious thought. Of great interest to me was his sympathetic take on nihilistic literature, often wrongly condemned as anti-humanistic. Nihilism arose in Western thought as a consequence of the “death of God” in Western epistemology. Suddenly, man no longer had a home in a world that now seemed alien, frightening and strangely “unnatural” to a being that materialists claim is nothing more than a biological product of the earth. <br /><br />Religion was the origin of the idea that all human beings inherently have rights and are inherently equal in creation. While the ghost of the idea of inherent human dignity and value continues to animate allegedly “secular” modern ideologies, this is a contradiction that is under constant siege by capitalism, socialism and technological advance. Deprived of the warmth of the concept of inherent human value and the natural dignity and purpose afforded by belief in divine creation, the world seems a potentially bleak and terrifying place – a predicament that nihilistic writers like Camus suggested raised the possibility of suicide as a natural response. <br /><br />According to Izetbegovic, this view of mankind as essentially a stranger in the world marks nihilism as an essentially religious yearning – the religion of those disappointed in not finding the divine. Both nihilism and religion effectively recognize the existence of a soul and an essential human foreignness to the world. The difference is religion claims to have found a way out, while nihilism does not. The difference between such a view and that held by strict philosophical materialists is significant. <br /><br />Izetbegovic cites Plato in his description of the idea of the body as the “grave of the soul,” and that, “an ethical man is not afraid of death…to truly think and live means constant preparation to die.” In Islam, submission to God and an acceptance of an external locus of control regarding worldly events is the only way out of the anxiety and unsatisfied yearning of human existence. But despite this, Islam does not denigrate the world. Indeed it encourages humans to take their enjoyment from what is made lawful to them, a message embodied in the Quran and life of the Prophet Muhammad which is often wrongly attacked by critics as an expression of sensualism and an insufficient “pure religiosity” within Islam. <br /><br />In the modern world, the religious worldview has been degraded and confused. Indeed, some ardent materialists are in practice self-sacrificing metaphysicians, while some ostensibly religious people are obsessed with materialism. The family unit has been degraded in the name of society, but society itself has been degraded by corrupt elites, leaving ordinary people nowhere to turn for comfort or support. On top of this, modern epistemologies have been obsessed with the creation of worldly utopias that essentially reduce man’s capacity for both moral or immoral action, not by nurturing mankind’s conscience but instead through basic drills and penalties. This effort may achieve some success at simply controlling the masses, but it reduces humans to nothing more than cogs in a machine or animals subject to discipline, albeit animals possessing the tool of rationality.<br /><br />It seems that with developments in technology and capitalism we are fast headed towards such a degrading future for mankind, whether we are aware of where are going or not. As Aldous Huxley predicted, human beings are beginning to merge with their technologies and become something other than “humans” in the traditional sense. This was arguably predicted as far back as Ibn Arabi and is reflected upon here in light of recent technological and social developments by Izetbegovic. Whereas religion sees life as a grand drama, modern civilization sees it as the processing of a soulless machine, where human beings are nothing more than inputs and outputs. Any surviving trace of the idea that all life has a supreme meaning and inherent value is a residue of religion, whereas ideologies like Marxism accord rights only on the basis of demands (hence its silence on the suffering of animals).<br /><br />Izetbegovic concludes with the fascinating argument that the Islamic worldview of “balance” lives on in the West, specifically in the Anglo-American tradition which retains both moral and materialistic components. Nations with Catholic histories have held onto the old dichotomy between the “Kingdom of Man” and “Kingdom of Heaven”, oscillating between the two during different periods in history and never succeeding in balancing them. Within the Anglo tradition, however, we see a retention of “the middle way” that integrates both and potentially allows for both a fruitful worldly and spiritual existence. With an eventful thirty years distance since this book was published its unclear how much of this balance remains in existence, but he argues convincingly that its roots helped stimulate the development of the Anglo world. <br /><br />This was a beautiful and nourishing book that I appreciated on both a spiritual and intellectual level. It is hard to live either in a world of pure religion or a world of pure materialism. Human beings are not built for either extreme. The idea of Islam as a balanced path between the two, a philosophy embodied in its most basic acts of prayer, fasting and charity, is a comforting vision of a world in which the various components of human existence have been brought into harmony. Izetbegovic ends the book with an ode to the Islamic worldview and the idea of submission to the divine will as the solution to the existential dilemmas of modern man. It’s a beautiful message to end on.</span>
  <a data-text-id="91345440429067139" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


