        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer137877163" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17915985077408082909">All I can say, book, is that we&apos;re off to a rocky start.<br/><br/>&quot;There are only three integral views of the world: the religious, the materialistic, and the Islamic(1).&quot; p. 25<br/><br/>First footnote:<br/><br/>&quot;(1)In this book, the term religion has the meaning it has in Europe - that is, faith as an esoteric experience which does not go beyond a personal relationship with God and as such expresses itself only in dogmas and rituals. Accordingly, Islam cannot be classifed as a religion. Islam is more than a religion for it </span>
  <span id="freeText17915985077408082909" style="display:none">All I can say, book, is that we're off to a rocky start.<br /><br />"There are only three integral views of the world: the religious, the materialistic, and the Islamic(1)." p. 25<br /><br />First footnote:<br /><br />"(1)In this book, the term religion has the meaning it has in Europe - that is, faith as an esoteric experience which does not go beyond a personal relationship with God and as such expresses itself only in dogmas and rituals. Accordingly, Islam cannot be classifed as a religion. Islam is more than a religion for it embraces life."<br /><br />Now, isn't that just about what every religion claims? Just wondering, book, just wondering.<br /><br />******************************************************************************************************<br /><br />There's only just so much dogma a reader can stomach in the name of even-handedness before nausea sets in. Let's just say that I've a weak belly and further reading could have been seriously injurious to my health.</span>
