    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3325447048" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3325447048" />
    <a title="Shuaib  Choudhry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/84096717-shuaib-choudhry"><img alt="Shuaib  Choudhry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608737393p2/84096717.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3325447048?book_show_action=true">Oct 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shuaib  Choudhry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shuaib  Choudhry" href="/user/show/84096717-shuaib-choudhry">Shuaib  Choudhry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780892590575" href="/book/show/825445.Islam_Between_East_and_West">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3325447048" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer147928241468062642">A real diamond of a book, perhaps my favourite ever, such is the eloquence, depth and breadth of this treasure. He covers the creative heights of fiction and art to the genius of the logicians and philosophers, but they all come unstuck in the inconsistency present in their own worldview; except Nietzsche, who took the ideas which form the bed rock of most modern western nations and showed their ultimate logical conclusion in nihilism. Many times I have personally heard that Islam is a religion </span>
  <span id="freeText147928241468062642" style="display:none">A real diamond of a book, perhaps my favourite ever, such is the eloquence, depth and breadth of this treasure. He covers the creative heights of fiction and art to the genius of the logicians and philosophers, but they all come unstuck in the inconsistency present in their own worldview; except Nietzsche, who took the ideas which form the bed rock of most modern western nations and showed their ultimate logical conclusion in nihilism. Many times I have personally heard that Islam is a religion of the middle path or the religion of moderation and it is something I could definitely feel but I could not quite convey it. No one has illustrated it in as beautiful a manner that Alija Izetbegovic does by showing that man himself is the one that sits at middle of endless dichotomies: religion and science, spirituality and materialism, subject and object, concrete-unique and abstract-general and many more. It's only Islam with its ideals and duties, congruent to man, sitting at the middle of these bottomless contradictory dichotomies. <br /><br />The author is aiming to provide a perspective of an Islamic outlook of the world. He starts with the premise that every philosophy can be reduced to two systems, the religious or the materialistic. Except one, Islam, which is a synthesis of both, thus ideally suited for man. The table he provides at the end of book is a superb rendering of this dualism. Islam means the call to create a man harmonious in his soul and body. Islam is a permanent search for a state of inward and outward balance. A way of life that is a moderation between these two demands of life. Man is inherently inconsistent, never solely logically consistent, and so one needs a dualistic philosophy which takes this nature of man into account. Islam provides this. Another way to see this is through Godel's incompleteness theorems and its consequences for humans and machines, which are in essence abstract logical systems. Man is not mechanistic in the computational sense because he has a spirit/soul and this is what provides him with creativity and hence intelligence beyond a mechanistic conception of these notions. I feel this is what Alija is trying to get across as the core theme of his message. Islam provides the only logically consistent way of life which takes the inherent nature of man into account, the materialist and the spiritual. Civilisation is the material exchange between man and nature, culture the spiritual exchange. These recurring dualisms are antagonisms and man's dualism show that man is a being of discord. <br /><br />The perspicacious author provides a sharp critique of education or technical education like science which is much more concerned with learning and applying but rarely contemplating. It's a perceptive look at the modern scientific method. "Science discovers, art creates" is a truly exceptional phrase from the author and shines a light on the façade of science; the fact that it does not encourage creativity but encourages conformity. Only once enough evidence, disproving current dogmas, has accumulated do geniuses, who think outside the current mode, get accepted and change the whole lens with which people view the world. Thomas Kuhn in his seminal book The Structure of Scientific revolutions provides much more detail then what I have given a taste of here, but this highlights the link to creativity within science and Kuhn's paradigm shifts. Science is focussed so much on logic and thus working within the current paradigm, creativity is lost and scientific progress stagnates once the revolution has passed. Scientific revolutions and paradigm shifts only come about through contemplative thinking, when one critically thinks about the systems in which they are working in/with. One needs both for the progress of society and man. <br /><br />Creativity is a purely human quality and only humans create in a unique fashion. This comes about because of the core human essence of the soul and the inherent freedom it was endowed with. This freedom allows us to choose between what's right and wrong and is the basis of free will. The uncertainty that results from this free and unique choice gives colour to the world and diversity in life, which links beautifully with the ideas from the book The Grammatical Man. Architecture, uniquely perhaps, is a balance between creativity and functionality and as such is the middle ground between the two. Thus it is harmonious to an Islamic ideal of art and perhaps partly explains why the zenith of Islamic art or cultural expression has been architecture. This marriage between the functional and the beautiful typifies Islam, combining the mathematics of geometry with the richness of colour. It also partly explains my fascination with architecture combining my yearning for mathematical expression with my need for human creative expression. <br /><br />The first two-thirds of the book I would recommend to anyone who is interested in learning about good critiques of some very popular philosophical systems and mainly deals with the duality of world views that religion and materialism provide and how they manifest themselves when you take their foundational conceptions to their ultimate logical aim. This book goes right to the core of what it means to be human by exploring the very human notions of morality, law, art, ethics and history to probe social, psychological, political and cultural questions in a comparative and dialectical manner; resulting in a comprehensive study of philosophies and world views. The final third tackles those very questions, which contemporary thought systems came undone by, and shows how Islam provides a way out of those internal conflicts that beset man. It's an incredibly stimulating book, from a spiritual and an intellectual perspective and one I'm sure to come back to many times over for the rest of my life. For me this book is truly timeless.</span>
  <a data-text-id="147928241468062642" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


