<div id="review_2348595550" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2348595550" />
    <a title="lifeofsadnan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11867188-lifeofsadnan"><img alt="lifeofsadnan" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2348595550?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="lifeofsadnan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="lifeofsadnan" href="/user/show/11867188-lifeofsadnan">lifeofsadnan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780892590575" href="/book/show/825445.Islam_Between_East_and_West">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2348595550" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16355374808367101367">NOT FOR CASUAL READING. this book took me forever to get through. i&apos;d open it, read 2 pages, and fall asleep. the language is complicated and it can get fairly dense/repetitive at times.<br/><br/>but learning wise, it is a great read. alija touches on many points - the creation of man, evolution, art/architecture/music, the modern world, morality, faith, god, the list goes on. even though I feel like i&apos;ll need to come back to it later to appreciate it fully, I feel like it&apos;s given me a good insight into t</span>
  <span id="freeText16355374808367101367" style="display:none">NOT FOR CASUAL READING. this book took me forever to get through. i'd open it, read 2 pages, and fall asleep. the language is complicated and it can get fairly dense/repetitive at times.<br /><br />but learning wise, it is a great read. alija touches on many points - the creation of man, evolution, art/architecture/music, the modern world, morality, faith, god, the list goes on. even though I feel like i'll need to come back to it later to appreciate it fully, I feel like it's given me a good insight into the application of islam in the modern world, how it is the natural solution to the malaise suffered by western individuality and society at large. <br /><br />Creation and evolution<br />Pg 10 - moral principles reduce man's efficiency<br /><br />Pg 18- animals play, but there is always a need for it<br /><br />Pg 19 - potlatch, celebrating by destruction of material objects<br /><br />Pg 20 - biology is about the phenomena of life, not their essence<br /><br />Pg 21 - the organism feeds on negative entropy from the outside. Life is a movement against the wind of mechanical laws<br /><br />Pg 28 - war years, replenishment of sexes<br /><br />Pg 30 - the tendency of the official materialism.<br /><br />Pg 31 - he eliminates questioning<br /><br />"no meditation is needed if everything is clear"<br /><br />Pg 32 - the appropriate conclusions on the organisation of society based on Darwin's idea of man from animal. Do Muslims beauracratise like this too?<br /><br />Pg 33 - look what the animals do and do the opposite, says religion<br /><br />Pg 34 - man may create an imitation of himself soon but it will only be able to do what it is programmed to do<br /><br />Pg 35 - there cannot exist a science about the soul<br /><br />Pg 37 - why are there so many handicapped people around the houses of good, who may stand and pray next to the healthy and may even be better than them, they who have nothing to prove. Equality comes from the common origin of man<br /><br />Pg 38 -education can be inhuman<br /><br />Culture and civilization<br /><br />Pg 44 - culture is all about the afterlife, even if in rejection<br /><br />Pg 45 - civilisation is technical progress<br /><br />Pg 46 - culture is self power, civilisation is power over the world<br /><br />Pg 47 - meditation to know one place in the world<br /><br />Pg 48 - learning is about science<br /><br />Pg 49 - meditation is not about intelligence<br /><br />Education is about usefulness to society<br /><br />Pg 51 - education in capitalist countries conforms to economic requirements. Generally education serves the system.<br /><br />Pg 53 - mass culture leads to spiritual uniformity. The endless supply of kitsch<br /><br />Popular culture is authentic<br /><br />Pg 55 - mass culture is of a puerile state of mind<br /><br />Pg 56 - machines help create uniformity<br /><br />Religiousness decreases as the city increases<br /><br />Pg 57 - the barracks of a big city, passive knowledge of mass media and surrounded by objects of mass production<br /><br />Religion belongs to life arts and culture, atheism belongs to method science and civilisation<br /><br />Pg 58 - the working class in countries with vastly more civilisation than culture, ie high influence of factories and technology, are least revolutionary<br /><br />Pg 59 - more and more, machines take manual work while man is tasked with managing large automatic systems<br /><br />Technocracy<br /><br />Pg 60 - no religion means no revolution<br /><br />Official institutions are neither revolutionary nor religious<br /><br />Pg 61 - more progress in last century years than last 40 centuries (Oppenheimer)<br /><br />Standards of living do not increase happiness or humanity<br /><br />Pg 62 - our planet is an ocean of delinquents<br /><br />Pg 63 - alcoholism in developed countries<br /><br />Pg 64 - porn as an escape from routine. Gambling too. Drugs too.<br /><br />Pg 65 - technology disappearing the spirit<br /><br />Men become less satisfied with the betterment of their life<br /><br />Half of hospital beds are for mental patient s<br /><br />Pg 67 - mental degradation and health problems are an expression of civilisation itself<br /><br />Pg 68 - pollution <br /><br />Pg 69 - pessimistic philosophy comes from rich nation s <br /><br />Comfort is the lease appearance but Human life in developed nations is absurd by default<br /><br />Pg 70 - serious plays emit absurdity, positivity comes from comedy and old musicals<br /><br />Poets are the sensors of mankind<br /><br />Suicide of renowned Japanese artists<br /><br />Pg 71 - nihilism and the philosophy of the absurd come from the richest posts of the world.<br /><br />Civilisations failure to solve the problem of human happiness, but don't people already know this?<br /> <br />Pg 72 - religious story of man's origin is true because the scientific one is false. <br /><br />Nihilism is a protest against God a absence<br /><br />Materialism gives life function but no purpose. World is a zoo<br /><br />Everything is futile, but don't some people express hope from this?<br /><br />Pg 73 - atheism of despair.<br /><br /> Absurdism<br /><br />Freedom sets its aims absolutely. <br /><br />Pg 74 - destroy the myth of civilisation<br /><br />The phenomenon of art<br />Pg 77 - religion and art suppose the existence of another order. <br /><br />Darwinism as a rejection of ethics<br /><br />Pg 78 - matter, life, personality as three realities, but science only deals with the first<br /><br />Pg 79 - science and art neither succeed not depend on each other<br /><br />Philosophy is closer to science than art<br /><br />Pg 80 - all of science is an almost mechanical continuation<br /> Art is a continuous new arising<br /><br />Pg 81 - science discovers art creates<br /><br />Art is more true<br /><br />Pg 82 - the failure of the analytical approach to art should tell us something<br /><br />Pg 83 - link between art and religion. Spirit, creation, mystery, sacred, transcendnence<br /><br />Pg 84 - drama is of a religious origin<br /><br />Pg 85 - early art was part of the ritual, later being separated<br /><br />Song of songs<br /><br />Science is a daughter of astronomy, art of religion<br /><br />Pg 86 - art at its best expression through religious themes<br /><br />Pg 87 - art inspired by presentiment, feeling of transcendency<br /><br />Pg 88 - when a body of governmental authority declares it's truth<br /><br />Pg 89 - education towards civilisation, recession of art, state atheism<br /><br />Pg 90 - lag of arts and philosophy in Soviet forced socialist realism<br /><br />Pg 91 - if people have no soul then why should cities have one<br /><br />Beautiful objects come from a time when we were poorer<br /><br />Pg 92 - sociology has the average man, art has the individual<br /><br />Man does not want to be systematised<br /><br />Pg 93 - the things come from America and pile up<br /><br />Philosophy and science talk about man in general<br /><br />Pg 94 - a thing described is a thing determined<br /><br />Pg 95 - passages describing unique situations<br /><br />Pg 96 - laws of art in opposition to the mechanical and the abstract<br /><br />Pg 97 - faces as central to art. <br /><br />Art deals with moral aspect of the subject<br /><br />Pg 98 - what lies at the heart of every painting is the personality in an alien world and a conflict emerging from this basic relation<br /><br /> The soul is not the psyche, it bears responsibility and dignity<br /><br />Jung's types vs an artist's created character, the former is a monster, the others are real men<br /><br />PG 99 - The Essence of art is a longing<br /><br />Inactivity full of action<br /><br />The work of art is destroyed by multiplication<br /><br />Pg 100 - when speaking about a work we actually speak about the author. It is important what the Peter painter himself is<br /><br />PG 101 - a bad man cannot be a good poet<br /><br />Kitsch<br /><br />Everything is the opposite in Civilization<br /><br />PG 102 - completely intelligible works of art do not exist<br /><br />Creation is the aim of art while the work is it's un finished symbol<br /><br />Pg 103 - style is inscrutable, function is reasonable<br /><br />Sheer aesthetic design becomes degenerate decor<br /><br />PG 104 - critique is rationalistic, but art is not of thought<br /><br />An artist is not an intellectual<br /><br />It would be easier for the average spectator to understand the message of a work than a critic<br /><br />The Bible and Quran are not theological books<br /><br />PG 105 - there is no unreligious art<br /><br />Morality <br />Pg 109 - morality isn’t functional or rational. <br />Do we think of defeated justice/unsuccessful actions as worthless? Eg carrying man out of burning building<br /><br />Pg 110 - Moral conduct is either meaningless or it has meaning and sense in the existence of God<br /><br />Pg 111 - rhetoric used by governments to show morality, even as hypocrites.<br />“Morality is not in the act, it is the desire to live righteously”<br /><br />Pg 112 - deeds judged by intentions (religion) or consequences (revolution/ideology): negation of world vs negation of man<br /><br />Pg 113 - “an action has no moral merit in itself; to learn the moral value of man, we have to look inside. Since we can’t do it directly, we pay attention to actions, but they only remain signs of inner will”<br />“A man is not what he does but what he wants”<br /><br />Pg 114/115 - “drill has no influence on the moral attitude of man” - “behaviour that does not engage our deepest will is not an upbringing, but a drill”<br />“Drill, even when used to implement the correct habits, is essentially immoral and inhuman”<br />Individualists: man’s conversion inwardly vs Positivists: outward behaviour<br />If crime is through free choice, external reeducation has little chance of success. If crime is through bad habits, offender can be drilled to remove these<br />NOT SURE I AGREE. <br />Deen? The basics of deen are drills (acts of worship). Noobs are encouraged to do them even if they dont have full yaqeen (ie even if you’re not the best muslim, you still have to give dawah, grow a beard. Even if you dont have full yaqeen you still need to pray 5x a day). <br />Actions of worship (drills) bring down the mercy of allah. You have to question whether it’s having an affect on your heart, but this isn’t something that we can accurately determine ourselves. At the end of the day the action does boil down to upbringing (essence/heart) but we can’t tell the difference it’s having on us, so we do it anyway<br />How many of our bad habits are drills? TV, excessive sports, internet use. Do we deeply desire these?<br /><br />Pg 116/117<br />Freedom is inseperable from ethics - just like how the laws of physics insert themselves into everything<br />“Reason’s (logical) analysis of morality reduces it to nature, selfishness and egoism”<br />Reason can not give moral judgement. Nothing can be proved to be “good” or “evil” using reason alone - nature doesn’t have this. Neither can values like “liberty, equality, fraternity” or teachings of Christ be derived from reason<br />Max it can go is societal morality - social discipline, again, drill.<br /><br />Pg 118/119<br />Science vs ethics/religion/art - euthanasia, artificial insemination. <br />Religion: life and death are in the hands of God<br />Ethics: degrade man to an object, leads to his manipulation and misuse<br />Art: birth and death are mysteries and should remain as such<br /><br /><br />NO LOGICAL ARGUMENT AGAINST THE ABOVE (we see this today with how ready people have become to accept euthanasia). Just 40 years ago it was the biggest taboo, now if you argue against it you’re immoral.<br /><br />Humanism vs biology, individualism vs materialism.<br />“Biology offers him progress in exchange for his soul and human dignity”<br />“Man refuses the progress which is at hand if he has to achieve it by means disgusting to him, but will he refuse it tomorrow? Will he always refuse it?”<br /><br />Pg 120/121<br />Pure vs practical reason (one can’t accept god, one has to) <br />Science conducted individually is a spiritual quest (the pursuit of knowledge, enlightenment, the joy of learning). When it is mechanised, broken into numbers, used for the state’s military or monetary gain, it becomes material and irreligious at it’s core.<br />“Through it’s innate rejection of metaphysics and its inevitable silence on ultimate questions, science contributes to the formation of atheistic opinions - maybe not with the scientist - but certainly with the public”<br /><br /><br />Pg 122<br />Religion = belief, Morality = belief transformed into action<br />“Morality was born by prohibition and has remained a prohibition until today… history of religion is full of seemingly meaningless prohibitions… Prohibition can have a rational meaning, but utility is never it’s primary aim”<br /><br />Pg 123<br />“Moral and physical evils of the world are the main driving forces that make us spiritual beings”<br /><br />Pg 124<br />“To truly think and live means constant preparation to die” - Plato<br /><br />Pg 126/127<br />Rationalistic negation of morality <br />Von Holbach: “All beings are looking for pleasure, and all of them are afraid of pain. They call good all that causes them pleasue, and evil all that causes them pain.” <br />Re consciousness “awareness of the influence which our conduct can have on the people that surround us, and remorse is the fear we feel at the thought that our conduct can make other people hate us or be angry with us”<br />“Religion is refined egoism. Seeks to transform desire for material pleasure into moral demand”<br />Eudaemonism: moral duty is what gives you personal well being, when your life is governed by reason. <br />Asceticism, celibacy, material sacrifice, sacrifice for principles - are these things that cause pleasure? They are viewed as the pinnacle of morality.<br />CONTEMPORARY BS: “Religion just exists to make you feel good about yourself and help you justify your actions.”<br />“Women and children first?” Does being honest help, why? Should look out for self interest<br /><br />Pg 128/129<br /><br />Morals are “what is useful”. Just because something is useful doesn’t make it right eg crime. “The more profitable the murder, the less chance the murder has of being arrested”<br /><br />Pg 131<br />Social behavior is promoted by interest/self preservation, moral behaviour is not. If moral behavior was (for the benefit of society materially), we would be like animals and instinctively do it.<br /><br />Pg 132<br />“Morality is only what helps the victory of the proliterat” - Lenin. Used to justify all the murder, abductions, political dissident deaths, killing of government critics, purges, etc..<br /><br />Pg 133<br />“Authentic morality is interested only in intentions… results and consequences are in God’s hands”<br /><br />Pg 134<br />All morality owes to a religion - even concepts of respecting elders, being nice to people, etc… <br />True godless society = 1984<br /><br />Pg 135<br />“Chinese Cultural Revolution” - Mao recognised that China’s cultural/spiritual inheritance was the biggest blockade to the material progress socialism needed. <br /><br />Pg 137<br /><br />Classic atheist argument: “If I, as a free human being, hear an inner voice, without anybody’s command, which tells me not to steal or kill… If I do not derive it from any kind of absolute, social or divine, then that is not a degradation of man.”<br />Translated: I am better than a religious person. A religious man needs a book to tell him what to believe, while I am le enlightened and know what’s right or wrong my myself.<br />Why this is BS: <br />Aren’t you making yourself your God? Whatever is good is what feels right to you. Isn’t this just another, lower form of religion?<br />Marx “hope in the abstract humanity of man is no less an illusion than the pure religious illusion”<br />Engels: “Every class and every profession has it’s own morality, and they break it whenever they can and go unpunished. The love which should unite everything manifests itself in wars, conflicts, family quarrels, divorces, and exploitation of other people”<br />I.e if everyone thought like this, the world would be a massive free for all. <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />Culture and History<br />Initial Humanism<br />“The present is always something more than the past and something less than the future”<br />Materialists: history = material progress<br />Spiritual: history = cultural progress, continual answering of eternal questions<br /><br />“I have seen human nature in all it’s aspects. It is the same everywhere, only the more wild it is, the more virtue is in it”<br />Makes sense if “wild” means technologically lacking<br />Yes, cultures of the east had virtue before. Does this mean western culture has no virtue? White people aren’t that bad??<br />Does this mean the routine in our lives? Does routine and comfort kill our virtue?<br />Quotes examples of American indian/African nations, how they marry, society structured, treat guests, etc… the civilized spanish slaughtered the native indians they so admired<br /><br />Art and Science<br />“In art, there is no accumulation of knowledge or experience as there is in science”<br />african/native american/islander art alongside european, even though these are underdeveloped regions<br />No further exprressive power with time<br />Questions of art are universal, science are temporal “in light of modern science, not one sentence written in these books [old science books by Aristotle] is true today”<br />“Scientists belong to their time only, poets to all times”<br /><br />Ethics and History<br />“Culture is all in the search, going back, starting anew”<br /><br />“Moral truths are constant”...”not influenced by time, place, or social circumstances”<br />Moral relativism: how does it line up with this? According to Alija most examples proving it always focus on formal behaviour vs the actual big moral.<br />Speak truth, don’t get angry, don’t hurt people, live simply, defend yours and others rights, earn your own bread, be friends with people, don’t cheat, etc… <br />Golden Rule/Categorical Imperative<br /><br />Artist and Experience<br />Picasso: 70 years of painting, 5 styles. None of them necessarily better than the other. Art is style and expression. Isn’t this that postmodern bs?<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br />Drama and Utopia<br />Ideal Society<br />Drama vs utopia: “man is evil vs the social environment is evil” - man has choice vs man is a bunch of chemical reactions<br /><br />Chinese Cultural Revolution - theater nearly completely died: no drama showcasing family or personal problems. Everything was perfect<br /><br />“There are no human or moral problems in utopia”<br />The aspiration of the modern world is utopia (even ours) - buy a house, live comfortably, have a nice stable job, couple kids, die<br />In the interest of society: social discipline, abolition of family relationships (nuclear family), art at service of state (news/mass media), education, equality of sexes in division of labour, uniformity, collectivism, censorship (ironically)<br /><br />Moral dilenmas are at the core of human existence<br /><br />Utopia and Morals<br />“Man is a social animal”<br />Very ineffective one, if he were meant to be, the mechanisms would be instinctive ie ants, bees, termites<br /><br />“There are no morals in communism” - Marxist assertion<br />It’s all an instinct, nobody willingly behaves morally, its inbuilt, instinctive<br />Spider doesnt think about whether it’s being moral when it eats its siblings after hatching, bees dont think bout it when they throw older bees out of the hive<br /><br />Quoting examples of animals in moral discussions is dumb. If they had a brain, bees would eat the nectar other workers gathered themselves.<br /><br />Dependents and Heretics<br /><br />Society and Community<br />Society = based on material needs, i need to buy this from you, you give me this, etc. Community = spiritual needs.<br /><br />Personality and the Social Individual<br />“[religion] is a passion and obligation, not a comfort or a way of better living”<br /><br />“Elimination of everything specifically human, particularly individuality and freedom, seems to be the basic condition for utopia”<br /><br />Utopia and Family<br />“Social principle carried… to a state of utopia, does not recognise the family anymore”<br />What function does the family serve besides rearing the child? The emotions and attachment do nothing for the state in helping to make this utopia<br />Having kids is a form of production<br />One part of society is dedicated to producing goods, while the other can be dedicated to producing consumers<br /><br />Engels: “the single family ceases to be the economic unit of society. Private housekeeping is transformed into a social industry.”<br />Daycare, school, aged care<br /><br />“Until the myth of the family, the myth of motherhood and maternal instinct is destroyed, women will continue to be subjugated”<br /><br />Footnote on this page is great<br /><br />“Family as man’s nest, mother as the first and irreplacable teacher” vs “utopias have alw</span>
