<div id="review_2520499967" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2520499967" />
    <a title="Humza" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18915645-humza"><img alt="Humza" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595788816p2/18915645.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2520499967?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Humza" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Humza" href="/user/show/18915645-humza">Humza</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780892590575" href="/book/show/825445.Islam_Between_East_and_West">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2520499967" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1327820510689763320">Islam Between East and West begins with the following verses from Alamma Iqbal’s Javid Nama: <br/><br/>&quot;Though it is from the East that the sun rises,<br/>showing itself bold and bright,<br/>without a veil, it burns and blazes with inward fire<br/>only when it escapes from the shackles of East and West. <br/>Drunk with the splendor it springs up out of its East<br/>that it may subject all horizons to its mastery, <br/>its nature is innocent of both East and West, <br/>though in origin, true, it is an Easterner.&quot;<br/><br/> It seems to me that what fo</span>
  <span id="freeText1327820510689763320" style="display:none">Islam Between East and West begins with the following verses from Alamma Iqbal’s Javid Nama: <br /><br />"Though it is from the East that the sun rises,<br />showing itself bold and bright,<br />without a veil, it burns and blazes with inward fire<br />only when it escapes from the shackles of East and West. <br />Drunk with the splendor it springs up out of its East<br />that it may subject all horizons to its mastery, <br />its nature is innocent of both East and West, <br />though in origin, true, it is an Easterner."<br /><br /> It seems to me that what follows in the remainder of the book is an elaboration of the meaning of these words. Throughout “Islam between East and West”, I found myself thinking back to Iqbal’s “Reconstruction of Religious Thought” because of the very evident influence of this work had on the author. Both crafted responses that aimed to satisfy the curiosity of the Westerner and settle the faith of the Muslim. This book brought down to earth long abstracted concepts such as time and space in the Islamic cosmology I had wrestled to grasp. Having led an extremely rich and interesting life himself, Izetbegović takes the reader on a journey through western literature, art, history, politics, and even science to show how all are ultimately manifestations of man’s yearning for ultimate truth. Particularly valuable is his “Table of Opposites” in the appendix. Here he divides worldviews into the “religious,” “Islamic,” and “materialistic.” Izetbegović elaborates on each of these broad categorizations in chapters such as “Drama vs Utopia,” “City vs Countryside,” and “Prayer vs Production.” Referencing everything from Dostoevsky to Renaissance sculptures, Izetbegović explores the worlds of western intellectual/religious life and Islam and ultimately decides upon them being simultaneously distinct, yet united (along with all traditions) in shared aspiration for truth.<br /><br /> In one my favorite passages, he skillfully traces Darwinian evolution’s impact upon society and belief within the context of the aforementioned schemas. After presenting the opposing worldviews of “pure religion” and “pure materialism” and demonstrating that they are essentially negatives of one another, Islam is presented as a “bipolar unity” that contains aspects of both while being neither. This section of the book nicely ties together the preceding portions and demonstrates how the Islamic worldview is not simply an average of the two extreme worldviews, but rather a synthesis in which Islam presents a reality inevitably containing some of the truths man has come to “on his own accord.” This book compelling forwards that Islam defies man-made categorization and is indeed a unique “bipolar unity.” Although the book can wade into abstraction at times, Izetbegović does an excellent job of providing real-world examples and evidence to convincingly make his case. Alongside Muhammad Asad and Iqbal, Alija Izetbegović has surely secured himself a place as an essential guide to whom anyone seeking to understand Islam in the modern age must turn.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1327820510689763320" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


