<div id="review_2769531337" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2769531337" />
    <a title="Z." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3441634-z"><img alt="Z." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483077134p2/3441634.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2769531337?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Z." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Z." href="/user/show/3441634-z">Z.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789770926796" href="/book/show/8064720">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2769531337" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5770989293785102473">This work served as Alija Izetbegovic&apos;s doctoral dissertation and has become a foundational text for a deep understanding of human being mind sets. The book is a journey through different schools of thoughts, where it shows where the humanity failed and where it succeeded.<br/><br/>It&apos;s a deep understanding of leading world views (West/Capitalism/religion - East/Socialism/materialism) shows why such philosophies have failed to give human beings what they need, the whole book is meant to offer the position</span>
  <span id="freeText5770989293785102473" style="display:none">This work served as Alija Izetbegovic's doctoral dissertation and has become a foundational text for a deep understanding of human being mind sets. The book is a journey through different schools of thoughts, where it shows where the humanity failed and where it succeeded.<br /><br />It's a deep understanding of leading world views (West/Capitalism/religion - East/Socialism/materialism) shows why such philosophies have failed to give human beings what they need, the whole book is meant to offer the position and role of Islam in the context of this sharp ideological conflict between "East and West”.<br /><br />The author addresses intellectually the parallelism or dualism of various concepts such as Culture and Civilization, Moral and Utopia, Society and Community, Morals and Religion, rill and Upbringing, Art and Religion, Art and Science, Religion and Revolution, etc), <br /><br />It’s well known that internal and the external worlds as two parallel lines that never cross philosophically, yet both of them are existed in the human beings. By differentiating between the idealism of religion and the atheism of materialism Izetbegovic argues that religion and materialism, are two poles which only Islam can reconcile and bring about their synthesis. <br /><br />He explains how materialism claims that humans are not free and only subjects to their environment and natural development and cannot be equal from that perspective (always stresses what is common to animals and humans). On the other hand religion stresses what makes them different; for example the concepts of freedom, dignity, equality and responsibility can only come from the religious perspective.<br /><br />If we understand Izetbegovit well, religion/Christianity is true but only half-way; materialism/Socialism is also true but also half-way, where as Islam being a synthesis of religion and materialism and the unity of "religion and materialism”.<br /><br />In terms of his behaviour and existential witness, Izetbegovic remained faithful to most of the ideas and views expressed in this work.<br /><br />The thing I liked most about this book is that it proofs the fact that it has always been _ possible in Islamic history to offer a provocative and an intellectual answer to the call of Islamic universalism even when the - author is not familiar with traditional Islamic sciences! Alija Izetbegovit did not study Islam formally or systematically, nor-as already mentioned-did he know Arabic. He was just hard-working and self-taught person.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5770989293785102473" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


