<div id="review_4396052763" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4396052763" />
    <a title="Ahmed Bahaa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/110499096-ahmed-bahaa"><img alt="Ahmed Bahaa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588118325p2/110499096.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4396052763?book_show_action=true">Feb 05, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ahmed Bahaa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ahmed Bahaa" href="/user/show/110499096-ahmed-bahaa">Ahmed Bahaa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4396052763" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10271108274254804856">The author was a president, philosopher, poet and fighter. He was a human being. It’s obvious the author was well versed on western philosophy. Sartre, Camus, jaspers, Heidegger, Diderot, Marx, among others. He was able to recall those philosophies and articulate them in short sentences to move forward with his arguments. He is putting forward the claim that we are living in a world where almost no absolutes exist, and even those, they will slowly keep disappearing. That reminds me of Nietzsche </span>
  <span id="freeText10271108274254804856" style="display:none">The author was a president, philosopher, poet and fighter. He was a human being. It’s obvious the author was well versed on western philosophy. Sartre, Camus, jaspers, Heidegger, Diderot, Marx, among others. He was able to recall those philosophies and articulate them in short sentences to move forward with his arguments. He is putting forward the claim that we are living in a world where almost no absolutes exist, and even those, they will slowly keep disappearing. That reminds me of Nietzsche when he announced the death of God. Everything is relative, everything undergoes the negotiation process and is in the market. Ironically, I just read a book and watched a complete discourse on that very subject taught at Harvard business school. He takes the perspective that it’s a purely material world. He also identifies Culture and Civilization uniquely. <br /><br />From reading this lengthy book the author is reminding us of something we forgot, Something that transcends the material world, that justifies Altruism, Truth, Justice, etc.. <br />The author identifies the “natural man; which is only the sum of matter” by starting with Evolutionism, Darwinism, Biologism, etc.,- he is content with those philosophies [ i.e Darwin, Marx, Freud, etc.] and confirm they can accurately explains that which is common between humans and animals. He then goes on to question that point in evolutionary time where men stopped running, hunting and gathering [ thus wasting time] and they took that time to draw, dance, pray, offer to gods, etc. – there must be something else besides the matter, something that justifies those expressions. Something that’s neither materialistic nor pragmatic. Sexual/economical. His dualist view dominates the book. <br /><br />He concludes that current social sciences and humanities disciplines are heavily built to deal with the “natural man”. The book touches heavily on philosophy and theory of culture, law, science, aesthetics and ethics. It’s also full of interesting stats from the 60s. 5/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="10271108274254804856" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


