<span id="freeTextContainer8912442536076346183"><blockquote><br/>``An animal does not revolt against his animal fate. Only man revolts, the only animal who refused to be so.” p.18<br/><br/>``Newton’s world is stable, logical, and continuous, as Darwin’s man is simple and one dimensional: he struggles for survival, he satisfies his needs and aims for a functional world. Nonetheless, Einstein destroyed Newton’s illusion and pessimistic philosophy, and the failure of civilisation does so with Darwin’s image of man. […] The philosophy of man, which for a long time has been</blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText8912442536076346183" style="display:none"><blockquote><br />``An animal does not revolt against his animal fate. Only man revolts, the only animal who refused to be so.” p.18<br /><br />``Newton’s world is stable, logical, and continuous, as Darwin’s man is simple and one dimensional: he struggles for survival, he satisfies his needs and aims for a functional world. Nonetheless, Einstein destroyed Newton’s illusion and pessimistic philosophy, and the failure of civilisation does so with Darwin’s image of man. […] The philosophy of man, which for a long time has been under the influence of Darwin’s straight-lined vision, now is waiting for its Einsteinian overthrow. This new conception of man, as compared with that of Darwin, will be the same as the relation between Einstein’s and Newton’s universe. If it is true that we rise through suffering and sink through enjoyment, it is because we are different from animals.” p.19-20<br /><br />``Here we should say that completely intelligible works of art do not exist. ``A work of art is primarily an inner problem, a secret, a problem of belief.” It is a confession only partly intelligible to others. ``Only one man can understand my pictures, and that is me,” […] Every work of art is in a sense autobiographic. […] every man is alone, everyone follows his own way. Thus, a protest of the audience against an unintelligible poem, picture, or sculpture is mainly the result of their nonunderstanding of the very essence of art.” p.102<br /><br />``Islam […] postulates for man a complete and full life. […] one is the natural desire for happiness and power; the other moral perfection, […] These desires contradict and exclude each other in logic only; in real life, they have come together in innumerable ways in our own life and before our eyes. Such a possibility has only been given to man, and man – this controversial being – can be defined by it.” p.225<br /></blockquote></span>
