<span id="freeTextContainer4179921004792363974">this work should be put on a shelf in the louvre or sth, and it can&apos;t be read just once! one of the many points that triggered my mental conscious was the similarity between religion &amp; art in general; the art in it&apos;s search of what&apos;s humanity is like it kinda became a god&apos;s seeker, even though the reality has agnostic artists, that doesn&apos;t change a thing! it goes back to our nature as a contradicted human beings, humans were always in need of a way to communicate spiritually unlike animals who a</span>
  <span id="freeText4179921004792363974" style="display:none">this work should be put on a shelf in the louvre or sth, and it can't be read just once! one of the many points that triggered my mental conscious was the similarity between religion &amp; art in general; the art in it's search of what's humanity is like it kinda became a god's seeker, even though the reality has agnostic artists, that doesn't change a thing! it goes back to our nature as a contradicted human beings, humans were always in need of a way to communicate spiritually unlike animals who are satisfied with adapting and fighting for living, from a long time even before religions were known, there's sth in us wanting this gap-spiritual- to be filled. </span>
